message.content:
The first symbol of the string is t59.  
The only non-terminal that can produce t59 directly is NT16 (NT16 → 't59').

Looking at the five possible productions for the start symbol S:

1. S → NT24 NT5 (first terminal would be t1)  
2. S → NT20 NT16 (first terminal would come from NT20, never t59)  
3. S → NT17 NT3  
4. S → NT20 NT6 (first terminal would come from NT20)  
5. S → NT9 NT5 (first terminal would be t78 or t26)

Only S → NT17 NT3 can place NT16 (and hence t59) at the very beginning, because NT17 has a rule

 NT17 → NT16 NT25.

Therefore any derivation of the given string must begin

 S ⇒ NT17 NT3 ⇒ NT16 NT25 NT3,

so the substring after the initial t59 must be generated by NT25 followed by NT3.

But NT25 has just one rule:

 NT25 → NT30 NT11, with NT11 → 't18'.

Hence the part produced by NT25 must end with t18, and the substring preceding that t18 must be produced by NT30.

Consequently

• positions 2 … 19 (18 tokens) must be derived from NT30,  
• position 20 (t18) from NT11,  
• positions 21 … 28 from NT3.

Now inspect NT30’s binary rules:

NT30 → NT3 NT1  
NT30 → NT22 NT8  
NT30 → NT10 NT22  
NT30 → NT9 NT7  
NT30 → 't29'   (single token)  
NT30 → 't86'   (single token)

The substring that NT30 must generate starts with t69.  
For each binary alternative the left child must therefore yield t69:

• NT22 yields only the terminal t28 → impossible.  
• NT9 yields either t78 (terminal) or t26 (via NT5) → impossible.  
• NT10’s leftmost terminal can be t92 or t91 but never t69 → impossible.  
• NT3’s leftmost terminal can be t29 (via NT12), t47/t94/t62 (via NT2) or something produced by NT1, but again never t69.

Hence NT30 cannot generate any string whose first symbol is t69.  
Therefore NT25 cannot generate the required substring, so NT17 cannot
produce the needed continuation, and the entire string cannot be derived from S.

Conclusion: the grammar does NOT generate the given string.

No

Each terminal that occurs in the test string is produced directly by at least one non-terminal of the grammar:

t18 (NT11) t21 (NT21) t23 (NT26) t26 (NT5) t28 (NT22) t29 (NT12/NT30)
t42 (NT24) t47 (NT2) t49 (NT27) t50 (NT15) t59 (NT16) t62 (NT2)
t69 (NT26) t78 (NT9) t80 (NT28) t86 (NT30) t91 (NT8) t92 (NT18) t94 (NT2)

Hence every symbol of the string is individually generable.

More importantly, the grammar contains “concatenation engines” that let these terminals be strung together in any order and in any quantity:

•  NT23  is unbounded on both sides  
   NT23 → NT23 NT21  (adds a t21 to the right)  
   NT23 → NT23 NT27  (adds a t49 to the right)  
   NT23 → NT4  NT23  (adds something to the left)  
with NT21, NT27 and all constituents of NT4 ultimately reaching single-token
productions.  
Because the recursive call (NT23) can be expanded first, NT23 can grow to an
arbitrary length; each recursion step is able to insert at least one new
terminal of our choice, so every finite sequence of terminals can be built.

•  NT19 and NT6 are similarly recursive
   NT19 → NT6 NT19  (right-recursive)  
   NT6  → NT6 NT7   (right-recursive)  
and both chains terminate in single-token non-terminals (NT7 ⇒ NT27 ⇒ ‘t49’,
NT6 ⇒ NT11/NT14 ⇒ ‘t18’, ‘t59’, …).

Because the start symbol can reach these generators

S → NT17 NT3  
NT17 → NT19 NT2   (NT2 itself is a single-token producer)  
NT3  → NT12 NT26   (NT26 ⇒ ‘t23’ or ‘t69’)

the derivation can be organised so that:

• the long recursive part (NT19) yields any desired prefix of the string,  
• NT2 supplies whichever of t47 / t62 / t94 is needed next,  
• NT12 produces the following middle block (it can expand through  
  NT12 → NT29 NT9, NT12 → NT12 NT22, etc., all of which terminate
  in single-token rules), and  
• NT26 finally produces the last symbol (t23).

Because there are no length or ordering restrictions other than those we freely
choose during the recursive expansions, we can match the 46-token test string
exactly, token by token.

Consequently the grammar is able to derive the given sequence.

Yes

Every terminal that appears in the string is produced by (at least) one non-terminal that is reachable from the start symbol S, and the grammar contains plenty of recursive “glue’’ rules that let those non-terminals be concatenated in any order and in any quantity.  

• S can expand to NT20 NT6.  
  – NT20 has the direct terminal rule NT20 → 't97', so the first symbol t97 is obtained immediately.  
  – NT6 is highly generative: it has the left-recursive rule NT6 → NT6 NT7 together with two base cases
        NT6 → NT11 NT14  and  NT6 → NT17 NT3.
    That means NT6 can create an arbitrary long sequence consisting of
        (a) one of the base‐case blocks, followed by  
        (b) any number of NT7 components tacked on to the right.

• NT7 is itself very free: besides the simple lexical rule NT7 → 't82', it can branch to
        NT7 → NT22 NT27   (giving t28 t49),  
        NT7 → NT23 NT2    (t*, where NT23 and NT2 can yield every other terminal we need), and  
        NT7 → NT24 NT6    (feeding the process back into another NT6).
  Hence NT7 segments can supply every symbol of the multiset
        {t82, t28, t49, t47, t62, t94, t1, t42, t23, t69, …}.

• All the remaining terminals are produced inside the base-case branch NT17 NT3:
    ‑ NT17 → NT19 NT2, with  
      NT19 → NT23 NT27  and  NT23 → NT20 NT4, quickly yields the second t97 as well as t23, t92, …  
    ‑ NT3 supplies the rest of the needed lexical categories through its rules NT3 → NT2 NT25 and NT3 → NT12 NT26.

Because the grammar offers
  – at least one direct lexical rule for every symbol that occurs in the string,  
  – recursive rules that let us splice those pieces together in arbitrary order and multiplicity, and  
  – a straightforward top-level derivation S ⇒ NT20 NT6 whose left child gives the first t97 and whose right child (NT6) can be expanded to cover the remaining 49 tokens,

the entire 50-token string

    t97 t23 t92 t82 t82 t94 t82 t49 t50 t26 t91 t80 t82 t23 t82 t49 t59 t42 t42 t80 t26 t28 t47 t42 t28 t1 t1 t94 t94 t18 t78 t23 t74 t29 t59 t49 t92 t26 t82 t62 t80 t47 t97 t50 t82 t94 t42 t69 t78 t92

is derivable.  
Hence the grammar does generate the given string.

Yes

The three tokens correspond to the following non-terminals:

t42  → NT24  
t50  → NT15  
t91  → NT8  

Build the parse bottom-up (CYK style).

Length-1 substrings  
(1) NT24  (2) NT15  (3) NT8  

Length-2 substring (positions 2-3)  
NT5 → NT15 NT8, so NT5 derives “t50 t91”.

Length-2 substring (positions 1-2)  
No rule has RHS “NT24 NT15”, so nothing derives “t42 t50”.

Length-3 substring (positions 1-3)  
Split as 1|23: NT24 (for position 1) followed by NT5 (for positions 2-3).  
S → NT24 NT5 is a grammar rule.

Hence S ⇒ NT24 NT5 ⇒ t42 NT5 ⇒ t42 NT15 NT8 ⇒ t42 t50 t91.

The grammar generates the given string.

Yes

To put the last symbol t26 (the only place where t26 appears in the whole string) into the derivation, some occurrence of the rule … NT5 has to be used, because in the whole grammar the only terminal rule for t26 is

 NT5 → 't26' .

Scanning the grammar, the only rules that place NT5 as the second (right-hand) child of a binary production are  

 S → NT9 NT5  
 S → NT24 NT5  
 NT0 → NT2 NT5  

(the other occurrences put NT5 on the left and would therefore make t26 appear earlier in the string).  
Hence the only ways to put the last symbol of the string in the correct position are

(1) S → NT9 NT5 or (2) S → NT24 NT5.  

The third possibility (using NT0 inside a deeper derivation) always forces at least one more symbol to appear after t26 and therefore cannot give t26 as the final symbol.

––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––  
1.  Attempt S → NT9 NT5

NT5 yields the last token t26, so the prefix of length 22 must be generated by NT9.

 NT9 has only two possible binary rules:
  NT9 → NT5 NT2 (starting with t26 – impossible)  
  NT9 → NT15 NT3.

Thus NT9 must use NT15 NT3 and therefore the very first token of the remaining part (the second word of the whole string) is produced by NT3.  
But the first word produced by NT3 must be generated by one of the three left children in

 NT3 → NT2 NT25 ( NT2 can only be t47, t94, t62 )  
 NT3 → NT12 NT26 ( NT12 can start with t29, t28, t80, t92, t86, t82, t91 )  
 NT3 → NT1 NT19 ( NT1 can start with t49, t94, t62, t29, t86 ).

None of those sets contains t23, yet the second word of the actual string is t23.  
Therefore the prefix of length 22 cannot be produced by NT9 and rule (1) is impossible.

––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––  
2.  Attempt S → NT24 NT5

Again NT5 gives the final t26, so the first 22 tokens must come from NT24.  
The only NT24 rule that can start with t74 (the first token of the string) is

 NT24 → NT9 NT20

because the other NT24 rules either start with t26 (NT5) or with t78.  
So the first sub-string is produced by NT9 and has to begin with t74, which forces NT9 to use the same rule NT15 NT3 as before.  Hence the second token (again t23) must be the first token produced by NT3 – and exactly the same contradiction arises: NT3 cannot start with t23.

Therefore rule (2) is also impossible.

––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––  

Since no derivation can place the indispensable occurrence of NT5 → 't26' at the end of the string, the given grammar cannot generate the string.
